def loaddata(URL, col_names):
    return pd.read_csv(URL, names=col_names, na_values="?")

def one_hot_encoding(data):
    """
    Transforms the dataframe into a one_hot_encoded dataframe.
    
    :param data: dataframe
    :return:     datframe with 300 more columns
    """
    letters = ["A", "C", "D", "E", "F", "G", "H", "I", "K", "L", "M", "N", "P", "Q", "R", "S", "T", "V", "W", "Y"]
    col_names = []
    seq_len = 15
    # generating the column names "0_A", "1_A" .... for evey position of the 15
    for index in range(seq_len):
        col_names += [str(idx) + "_" + letter for idx, letter in zip([index]*20, letters)]

    # adding those columns to the dataframe with default value 0
    data = data.join(pd.DataFrame([[0]*seq_len*20], index=data.index, columns=col_names))
    # iterating over the rows and fixing the column values
    for i in xrange(len(data)):
        seq = data.loc[i, 'Seq']
        for index in xrange(len(seq)):
            data.loc[i, str(index) + "_" + seq[index]] = 1
    return data

sequence = loaddata('Sequences_train.csv', ['Seq', 'Class'])
sequence = one_hot_encoding(sequence)
sequence.loc[sequence.Class == -1, 'Class'] = 0

X = sequence.drop(['Class', 'Seq'], 1)
Y = sequence.Class

GridSearch on some hyperparams:¶

NN take a long time to train and they have a lot of hyperparams to tune, so doing a gridsearch is not really feasible. However, I tried to gridsearch on smaller subsets of hyperparams at a time and on only 50% of the data. I know this is not ideal, since hyperparams interact with each other and gridsearching on 2 parameters can give parameters that are not the best when combined with the rest of hyperparameters, but it was more of an initial guideline so get a feeling of what's appropriate for this problem.

Typically I was looking for parameter setting that would outperform their counterparts with the minimal NN arch. Then, I would combine those best params and hoepfully get the best results.

In [86]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense
from keras.layers import Dropout
from keras.wrappers.scikit_learn import KerasClassifier
from keras.constraints import maxnorm

def GridSearch(model, grid_params):
    since = time()
    grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=grid_params, n_jobs=1, verbose=3, cv=2)
    grid_result = grid.fit(X, Y)
    # summarize results
    print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
    means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
    stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
    params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
    for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
        print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))
    print "processing time: %f" % ((time() - since) / 60)

X, _, Y, _ = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.5, random_state=42)

def create_model(neurons=1, layers=2):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(neurons, input_dim=300, activation='relu'))
    for i in xrange(layers-1):
        model.add(Dense(neurons, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=create_model, epochs=50, batch_size=100, verbose=0)
neurons = [25, 50, 100, 200, 300]
layers = [1, 2, 3]
grid_params = dict(neurons=neurons, layers=layers)
GridSearch(model, grid_params)

def create_model(activation='relu'):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(100, input_dim=300, activation=activation))
    model.add(Dense(100, activation=activation))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=create_model, epochs=50, batch_size=1000, verbose=0)
activation = ['softmax', 'softplus', 'softsign', 'relu', 'tanh', 'sigmoid', 'hard_sigmoid', 'linear']
grid_params = dict(activation=activation)
GridSearch(model, grid_params)

def create_model(init_mode='uniform'):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(100, input_dim=300, kernel_initializer=init_mode, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(100, kernel_initializer=init_mode, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer=init_mode, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='Adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=create_model, epochs=40, batch_size=120, verbose=0)

In [117]:
def plot_hyperparams(fits):
    plt.clf()
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (25,15)
    f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    axes = axes.ravel()
    f.set_dpi(300)
    ind = 0

    validation_accuracy = fit.history['val_acc']
    training_accuracy = fit.history['acc']
    plot(validation_accuracy, 'Validation Acc', training_accuracy, 'Training Acc',
         "best acc %f" % (max(validation_accuracy)), axes[0])

    validation_loss = fit.history['val_loss']
    training_loss = fit.history['loss']
    plot(validation_loss, 'Validation Loss', training_loss, 'Training Loss',
         "Bmin loss %f" % (min(validation_loss)), axes[1])

    f.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
    plt.show()

for fit in fits:
    print fit.model.optimizer
    print 'Batch Size: %d, Epochs: %d' % (fit.params['batch_size'], fit.params['epochs'])
    print fit.model.summary()
    plot_hyperparams(fit)

The last model performed the best resulting in the best accuracy and the lowest loss trend. It's surprising because it's a very simple model with 1 hidden layer with 50 neurons. However, when we did the feature importance last assignment using randomforests on this dataset, there were only few columns that were very important in deciding the class, so maybe the net figured this out and that's why only 50 neurons were enough in yielding the best results.
